Daily-Level GAM Analysis of Monarch Butterfly Abundance: Results Summary

Author

Kyle Nessen

Published

September 30, 2025

Executive Summary

This analysis examines how previous day weather conditions affect day-to-day changes in overwintering monarch butterfly abundance using Generalized Additive Mixed Models (GAMMs). The analysis was motivated by field observations suggesting that monarchs respond to wind by relocating to more sheltered positions, and by a need to examine effects over longer time horizons than the 30-minute interval analysis.

Key Findings:

  • The analysis tested 105 models examining both absolute and proportional (density-dependent) effects of environmental variables
  • Models including previous dayâs butterfly count as a baseline performed substantially better (ÎAIC > 50)
  • The best-supported models indicate complex, non-linear relationships between environmental variables and butterfly abundance changes
  • Wind effects are present but show unexpected patterns that warrant careful interpretation

1. Motivation and Background

Why a Daily-Level Analysis?

The impetus for this analysis came from discussions with Jessica Griffiths, who expressed skepticism about the absence of wind effects in the 30-minute interval analysis. Both she and I have observed monarchs at Pismo relocating in response to windâspecifically moving to the leeward side of trees when exposed to strong south winds. These observations, combined with Kingston Leongâs documented observations of wind effects, suggested the need for a different analytical approach.

Key rationale:

  1. Longer time horizons: Day-to-day changes may capture more durable behavioral responses (persistence vs.Â emigration) than instantaneous counts
  2. Reduced temporal noise: Using daily peak counts removes confounding effects of diurnal movement patterns (morning dispersal, afternoon cluster reformation)
  3. Different response mechanisms: Unfavorable conditions on day t-1 may lead to emigration detectable on day t

Why Use Peak Counts?

Rather than analyzing counts at arbitrary time points, we use the 95th percentile of each dayâs counts. This approach:

  • Captures the maximum cluster size when butterflies are present
  • Controls for measurement timing uncertainty
  • Provides a robust measure less sensitive to outliers than the raw maximum
  • If butterflies emigrated, the peak count would be markedly lower

The 24-Hour Time Window

We examine previous day conditions affecting next-day abundance because:

  • This represents a plausible biological response window
  • Longer time horizons introduce uncertaintyâwe cannot track individual butterflies, only count populations
  • Beyond 24 hours, we lose confidence that weâre observing the same population that experienced the initial conditions

2. Data Structure

Dataset characteristics:
- Observations: 103 day-pairs
- Deployments: 7 
- Date range: 2023-11-19 to 2024-02-03 
- Temporal structure: Consecutive days within deployments

Response Variable: Square-root transformed difference in 95th percentile butterfly counts between consecutive days (butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt)

  • Selected as the most normally distributed transformation (normality score: 0.81)
  • Sign-preserving transformation: maintains direction of change
  • Positive values = increase in abundance; negative values = decrease

3.3 Wind Metrics (Previous Day)

Wind metrics from previous day
Variable Description Units
wind_avg_sustained_t_1 Mean sustained wind speed during daylight hours m/s
wind_max_gust_t_1 Maximum wind gust speed recorded (strongest wind event) m/s
wind_gust_sum_t_1 Sum of all gust speed measurements (cumulative wind exposure) m/s
wind_gust_sum_above_2ms_t_1 Sum of gust speeds when wind >2 m/s (threshold-weighted exposure) m/s
wind_gust_hours_t_1 Integral of gust speed over time (gust-hours of exposure) gust-hours
wind_minutes_above_2ms_t_1 Number of minutes with wind <U+2265>2 m/s (duration above activity threshold) minutes
wind_gust_sd_t_1 Standard deviation of gust speeds (wind variability/gustiness) m/s
wind_mode_gust_t_1 Most frequent gust speed in 0.5 m/s bins (typical wind condition) m/s

Wind variable selection rationale:

  • Most wind metrics are highly correlated with each other (see Section 3.4)
  • Standard deviation of wind showed low correlation (r=0.76 with max gust) but was excluded for simplicity
  • Chose wind_max_gust_t_1 for biological interpretability and consistency with 30-minute interval analysis
  • Threshold-based metrics (minutes above 2 m/s, etc.) were excluded due to high correlation with max gust

3.4 Correlation Matrix: All Candidate Predictors

This correlation matrix shows all potential fixed effects initially considered. High correlations (|r| > 0.75) indicate redundancy between variables.

Key observations from full correlation matrix:

  1. Temperature metrics are highly intercorrelated (r > 0.80):
    • temp_max, temp_mean, temp_at_max_count, hours_above_15C, degree_hours_above_15C
    • temp_min shows moderate correlation with other temperature metrics
  2. Wind metrics are highly intercorrelated (r > 0.75):
    • wind_max_gust, wind_gust_sum, wind_gust_hours, wind_minutes_above_2ms
    • All measure similar aspects of wind exposure with different emphases
  3. Between-category correlations:
    • Negative correlation between wind metrics and temperature metrics (r â -0.4 to -0.5)
    • Suggests windy days tend to be cooler
  4. Butterfly-environment correlations:
    • Previous day butterfly counts show weak correlations with most environmental variables
    • sum_butterflies_direct_sun shows moderate positive correlation with temperature metrics

5. Modeling Approach

5.1 Two Model Families: Absolute vs.Â Proportional Effects

We tested 105 models in two distinct families to distinguish different mechanisms by which environment affects abundance:

M Models (n=50): Absolute Effects

  • Do NOT include previous dayâs butterfly count
  • Test whether environmental variables cause fixed-magnitude changes regardless of population size
  • Example: âStrong wind reduces abundance by X butterfliesâ

B Models (n=55): Proportional/Density-Dependent Effects

  • Include butterflies_95th_percentile_t_1 as covariate or interaction term
  • Test whether environmental effects scale with baseline population
  • Example: âStrong wind reduces abundance by X% of the populationâ

5.2 Model Specifications

Within each family, models varied in:

  1. Fixed effects structure:
    • Single predictors vs.Â combinations
    • Linear terms vs.Â smooth terms (splines)
    • Main effects only vs.Â interactions
    • Different temperature metric combinations
  2. Random effects (all models):
    • Random intercept: deployment_id
    • Temporal autocorrelation: AR1 within deployments using day_sequence | deployment_id
  3. Correlation structures tested:
    • No temporal correlation (baseline)
    • AR1 correlation within deployments

5.3 Sample Model Formulas

Simple M models (absolute effects):

M1: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ 1
M2: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ wind_max_gust_t_1
M24: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ s(wind_max_gust_t_1)

Complex M models:

M34: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ s(temp_at_max_count_t_1) + s(wind_max_gust_t_1) + s(sum_butterflies_direct_sun_t_1)
M41: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ temp_at_max_count_t_1 * wind_max_gust_t_1

B models (proportional effects):

B1: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ butterflies_95th_percentile_t_1
B19: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ butterflies_95th_percentile_t_1 + temp_at_max_count_t_1 + wind_max_gust_t_1 + sum_butterflies_direct_sun_t_1
B31: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ butterflies_95th_percentile_t_1 + s(temp_at_max_count_t_1) + s(wind_max_gust_t_1)
B51: butterfly_diff_95th_sqrt ~ butterflies_95th_percentile_t_1 * wind_max_gust_t_1

6.2 Key Findings from Model Selection

  1. Density-dependence is critical: B models vastly outperform M models (ÎAIC > 50)
    • Environmental effects scale with population size
    • Cannot understand day-to-day changes without accounting for starting population
  2. AR1 correlation structure preferred: Models with temporal autocorrelation fit better
    • Day-to-day changes are not independent
    • Consecutive days within deployments are correlated
  3. Non-linear relationships: Smooth term models generally outperform linear models
    • Relationships between environment and abundance change are complex
    • Simple linear effects inadequate to capture response patterns
  4. Model uncertainty: Multiple models with ÎAIC < 2 indicates:
    • No single âbestâ model stands out
    • Different variable combinations provide similar explanatory power
    • Results should be interpreted with appropriate uncertainty

9. Discussion

9.1 Evidence for Environmental Effects

Baseline abundance is paramount: - All well-supported models include previous day butterfly count - Environmental effects are proportional to population size, not absolute - This suggests environmental factors modulate existing population trends rather than driving them

Temperature effects: - [Summary based on actual results]

Wind effects: - Present in top models but show complex, potentially non-intuitive patterns - Effect magnitude and significance vary with model specification (p â 0.08 in some versions) - Curve shape may be influenced by data artifacts (single day with zero wind) - More data might flatten or stabilize these patterns

Sun exposure: - [Summary based on actual results]

9.2 Comparison with 30-Minute Interval Analysis

This daily-level analysis does not contradict the 30-minute interval analysis:

  • 30-minute analysis: No detectable wind effect on instantaneous counts
  • Daily analysis: Some evidence for wind effect on day-to-day persistence, but:
    • Effect is model-dependent and marginally significant
    • Relationship is complex and not easily interpretable
    • May represent population-level behavioral decisions (emigration) vs.Â instantaneous movement

9.3 Limitations and Caveats

Sample size: - Only ~100 day-pairs vs.Â thousands of observations in 30-minute analysis - Weaker statistical power for detecting effects - Greater model uncertainty (multiple models with ÎAIC < 2)

Time horizon constraints: - 24-hour window chosen to balance biological plausibility with tracking uncertainty - Cannot follow individual butterflies; only observe population counts - Longer time horizons would introduce ambiguity about population identity

Wind effect interpretation: - Unexpected curve shape raises questions about biological plausibility - Single outlier point (zero wind day) may drive unusual pattern - Whether pattern is real or artifact requiring replication unclear

Residual model diagnostics: - While improved over 30-minute analysis, residuals still show some structure - AR1 correlation handles some but not all temporal dependence - Additional random effects or correlation structures might improve fit

9.4 Biological Interpretation

If wind effects are real (acknowledging uncertainty):

  • Largest decreases at zero wind is counterintuitive
  • Possible explanations:
    • Confounding with unmeasured variables (e.g., temperature inversions, microclimatic conditions)
    • Non-linear interaction between wind and temperature not captured by model
    • Artifact of limited sample size and data range

Field observations (Jessica Griffiths, personal observations) clearly show monarchs moving in response to wind. However: - These are short-term, within-site movements - May not translate to day-to-day emigration captured by peak counts - Different temporal and spatial scales between field observations and this analysis

9.5 Recommendations for Future Work

  1. Increase sample size: Additional years of data would:
    • Stabilize partial effect estimates
    • Improve power to detect effects
    • Allow assessment of year-to-year consistency
  2. Investigate zero-wind day: Detailed examination of the single day with previous wind = 0
    • Is this a data quality issue?
    • What were other conditions on that day?
    • Does excluding it change inference?
  3. Alternative time windows: Test 48-hour, 72-hour lags to understand temporal dynamics
    • Do effects accumulate over multiple days?
    • Is 24 hours the right response window?
  4. Individual tracking: If feasible, mark-recapture or GPS tracking would:
    • Distinguish movement from mortality/emigration
    • Directly test within-site relocation vs.Â leaving
    • Connect field observations to population-level patterns
  5. Microclimate measurements: Finer-scale environmental data at cluster locations
    • Temperature and wind measurements at cluster height
    • Sun exposure and shade mapping
    • Within-tree spatial heterogeneity

10. Conclusions

This daily-level analysis provides a complementary perspective to the 30-minute interval analysis:

  1. Baseline population size is critical: Day-to-day changes in abundance cannot be understood without accounting for the starting population (all top models are B models)

  2. Complex environmental relationships: Non-linear smooth terms outperform linear effects, indicating that environmental responses are not simple or monotonic

  3. Wind effects remain ambiguous: Some evidence for wind effects at daily timescales, but:

    • Effect size and significance are model-dependent
    • Curve shapes are difficult to interpret biologically
    • Potential data artifacts warrant caution

  4. Complementary to prior analysis: Results do not contradict the 30-minute interval findings

    • Different temporal scales may capture different processes
    • Instantaneous movement vs.Â emigration decisions

  5. Sample size matters: Limited data (~100 observations) constrains inference strength

    • Multiple competitive models indicate uncertainty
    • Additional years of data would strengthen conclusions

This analysis demonstrates that environmental effects on monarch abundance are complex and scale-dependent. While it provides some support for wind effects over daily timescales, the mechanisms remain unclear and warrant further investigation with additional data and refined methods.
